AUDIO: 'simple and use CapCut. I\'ve already made a new project, and if you don\'t really know how to edit yet, don\'t stress. This part is actually pretty easy. What I usually do first is import my whole project folder into CapCut. The reason is I like keeping everything organized'

[23:09] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'in one place. All my voice-overs, music, footage, everything goes into a single folder per project. So, I just bring that folder into CapCut, click on it, and make sure all my assets are there'

[23:21] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and ready to go. Now, the first thing I\'m going to do is drag my voice-overs onto the timeline. Since we generated them in batches, I just line them up so everything flows properly from start to finish. After that, I\'ll drag in the background'

[23:34] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'music and place it underneath the voice-over. Then, I\'ll trim the music so it matches the exact length of the voice-over. I don\'t want it going longer than the narration. Once that\'s done, I\'ll add a fade in and fade out so it doesn\'t just come in or cut out'

[23:47] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'abruptly. Then, I\'ll lower the music volume so it stays subtle in the background and increase the voice-over volume slightly so it always stays clear and on top. Now, the cool thing is most of the footage we generated already'

[23:59] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'comes with built-in sound effects. So, we don\'t really have to worry about adding extra audio for that. I actually like how a lot of these models now automatically generate sound effects per scene. It just makes everything feel way more complete. So, at this point, all you\'ve got to do is start dragging your'

[24:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
